tiple complementary and dissonant approaches. It employs a multiplicity of scholarly and critical lenses, including the intertextual history of medieval women’s literary culture, medical humanities, history of science, digital humanities, literary criticism, oral history, the global Middle Ages, archival research and creative re-imagining. Revealing several new discoveries about Margery Kempe and her Book in its global contexts, and offering multiple ways of reading the Book in the modern world, it will be an essential companion for years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian pilgrims and pilgrimages in literature. 0aChristian womenxReligious lifezEngland. 4aLiterature Studies 2022. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aJerusalem.  aMargaret Florentine.  aMechthild of Hackeborn.  aPilgrimage.  aThe Global Middle Ages.  aautobiography.  aecocriticism.  aemotion.  aoral history.  aperformance.1 aBale, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiosuè, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKalas, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKalas, Laura, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKim, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoster, Josephine A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Katherine J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaddock, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAvoy, Liz Herbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalih, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/